# Reading One — The Threads That Connect Everything

## How Binary Exploitation, Reverse Engineering, Cryptography, Forensics, and General Skills Operate as a Single Discipline

---

There is a version of CTF preparation that treats each category as its own island. You study binary exploitation in one block, cryptography in another, forensics in a third, and you assume that the skills you build in each column stay in that column. This is how most people start. It is also, eventually, why most people plateau.

The longer you spend competing — and the harder the challenges get — the more obvious it becomes that this model is wrong. The categories are not islands. They are nodes in a network, and the connections between them are not incidental. They are structural. Understanding those connections is what separates someone who can solve the easy and medium challenges from someone who can work their way through the hard ones consistently.

This reading is about those connections. It is not a guide to any specific challenge. It is a reflection on what this competition made clear about how these disciplines relate to each other, and why treating them as interconnected from the start produces better results than treating them as separate subjects that happen to appear on the same scoreboard.

---

## Binary Exploitation and Reverse Engineering Are the Same Skill Wearing Different Clothes

The most obvious connection in this competition was between binary exploitation and reverse engineering. On the surface they look like different problems. Reverse engineering asks: what does this program do? Binary exploitation asks: how do I make this program do something it was not supposed to do? But the moment you start working through harder challenges in either category, you realize that answering one question almost always requires answering the other first.

You cannot exploit a binary you do not understand. That is not a guideline, it is a hard constraint. A buffer overflow is only useful if you know where the overflow is, how much space you have before you reach the return address, what protections are in place, and what code you can redirect execution to. None of that information is handed to you. You have to read the binary, understand its structure, and build a mental model of what is happening at the memory level before a single byte of exploit code makes sense.

Reverse engineering without the lens of exploitation is also incomplete. When you are tearing apart a stripped binary to understand what it does, knowing which patterns are exploitable changes what you pay attention to. You start flagging things — unchecked input lengths, format string arguments, suspicious function calls — not just because they help you understand the program, but because they might be the vulnerability. The two disciplines train the same underlying muscle: the ability to read a program at a level below what the source code would tell you, and reason about its behavior from first principles.

Working through both categories back to back made this concrete in a way that reading about it never quite did. The tools are the same. The thinking process is the same. The difference is only in what you are trying to produce at the end.

