## Cryptography Lives Inside Binaries More Than People Expect

The second connection that became clear during this competition was between cryptography and binary exploitation and reverse engineering. Cryptography challenges are often presented as pure mathematical problems — here is a ciphertext, here is some partial information about the key, figure out the plaintext. And many of them are exactly that. But a significant number of the harder cryptography challenges this year had a binary component.

The encryption logic was not described in the challenge text. It was implemented in a binary that you had to reverse engineer first. The vulnerability was not in the mathematics in the abstract — it was in how the mathematics had been implemented in code. A classic cryptographic construction that is secure in theory can be broken completely by a single implementation mistake: a nonce that gets reused, an IV that is predictable, a key derivation function that leaks information through timing, or an RNG that produces output with too little entropy.

Finding those mistakes requires reading code. It requires the same static analysis skills you build doing reverse engineering. It requires the same attention to memory layout and data flow that makes you effective at binary exploitation. Someone who has only ever studied cryptography as a mathematical discipline and never spent time reading disassembled code will struggle with challenges that blur these lines.

The practical lesson here is that cryptography knowledge without implementation literacy has a ceiling. You can recognize an RSA small exponent vulnerability in a challenge that tells you the parameters explicitly. You are in much better shape if you can also recognize it when the RSA parameters are buried in a binary and you have to extract them yourself before the math even starts.

