## General Skills Is the Foundation That Nobody Talks About

General skills is the category that gets the least discussion in CTF write-ups, and that is a mistake. The challenges in this category are often the easiest on the scoreboard, which leads people to treat it as warmup material rather than a discipline worth taking seriously. But what general skills actually teaches — and what this competition reinforced — is comfort at the command line and a genuine understanding of how Unix systems work at a low level.

Every other category in this competition touched the command line. Running binaries, piping output between tools, writing quick Python scripts, redirecting files, reading man pages under time pressure, using netcat to interact with remote services — these are not optional skills that you can work around. They are the substrate that everything else runs on. Someone who is not fluent here is slower at everything, even if they understand the underlying concepts perfectly.

There is also a category of general skills challenges that are not about command line fluency at all, but about encoding and data representation — base64, hex, binary, URL encoding, various cipher alphabets. These come up constantly as sub-problems inside forensics and cryptography challenges. Recognizing encoded data on sight, knowing immediately which decoder to reach for, and being able to chain multiple decoding steps without losing the thread — these are skills that look trivial in isolation but save significant time in the middle of a harder challenge.

---

## What Working Through All of Them Reveals

The thing that working through all of these categories in a single competition makes clear is that cybersecurity is not actually a collection of separate skills that happen to share a name. It is one skill — the ability to understand systems at a level below what they are designed to show you — expressed across different surfaces.

A binary is a system. A cryptographic protocol is a system. A file format is a system. A network packet is a system. The underlying question in every category is the same: does this system behave exactly as described, and if not, what does the gap between the description and the reality allow you to do? Every category trains a different aspect of the ability to answer that question. None of them answers it fully on its own.

The competitors who perform best across all categories are not the ones who have memorized the most tools or practiced the most challenge types. They are the ones who have internalized this common underlying question deeply enough that they can apply it to unfamiliar surfaces quickly. That takes time, and it takes exposure to all of the categories — not sequentially, but in parallel, so the connections between them become visible.

